Was visiting Washington DC when I stopped by this place with friends for dinner. The environment is very nice and clean, the staff are friendly, and the food is pretty good. A lovely Chinese restaurant with a beautiful interior, great service, and decent food. I went here with a large group (50+ people) to celebrate Lunar New Year and it was a really enjoyable experience. The restaurant was well-decorated and the staff was super friendly and accommodating. The furnishings and decor made it a really enjoyable dining experience and great location for photos, and the overall restaurant had a wonderful and relaxing atmosphere. The food was pretty good, but there wasn't really anything special about it. It was an enjoyable dinner overall and I'd definitely be willing to try it out again!

I stopped into Chalin's for a relaxing dinner after work.  I've been here before, but this will be the first review.  Chalin's is  worthy of ALMOST 4 stars with an A atmosphere, A service and B - food.  The atmosphere is quiet, cozy and pleasant.  Raised views, comfortable seating and rustin chinese art make for a very enjoyable experience.  The servers are accommodating, fast, polite and very respectful - you feel like a guest, more than a customer.  The food - excellent hot n sour soup, tangy with just enough spice and very hearty.  Next I tried the  vegetable dumplings steamed.  They were plump, great texture but lacked flavor.  The veggie filling needs independent seasoning.  They were satisfying with tons of sauce.  Entree was "mushroom chicken."  The white sauce was surprising good but the dishes components weren't that exciting.  It was cooked well but the mushroom needed to shine, adding deep mushroom flavor to the sauce would have been great.  Still, I enjoyed the dinner.  Most certainly try Chalins, just be prepared to add a sauce or two.

I have eaten here once a month for nearly 2 years. Unfortunately the food quality here is very inconsistent. When the food is good, it's great for the price and taste (4 star worthy). But when it's bad,  the food quality is enough to make you wonder if this place even deserves 1 star.  Yesterday evening was my latest (and last) order - the sesame chicken was purely disgusting, unrecognizable as a dish. Each bite of the chicken left a mildly bitter after taste, reminiscent of rancid oil used to cook other meats or seafoods. The breading of the chicken was very thin and almost non-existent. It almost appeared like the breading was watered down severely perhaps in a last ditch effort to stretch out ingredients. The typical sweet flavor of Sesame chicken sauce was not there. My date got the Singapore noodles and the noodles tasted slimy, with some sort of burnt after taste.  Like I said though, on some occasions the food has been good. But when the above example happens, it makes you wonder why you are shelling out $14 for one dish that you barely ate, threw out and nearly vomited while sampling. To be clear, variations of the above example have happened on some other orders of Sesame Chicken, so the above incident is not isolated or an exception.  Please improve your sesame chicken and don't use old oil, or at least check to make sure the ingredients used are fresh and that the dish is acceptable tasting before serving to customers.
